==English==

===Verb===
{{en-verb|lives the dream|living the dream|lived the dream}}

# {{lb|en|idiomatic}} To [[experience]] the achievement of every [[success]] that one has aspired to achieve, especially from a [[career]].
#* '''1991''' June 19, Sara Rimer, "[http://www.nytimes.com/1991/06/19/nyregion/high-school-heroes-after-the-last-time-up.html?pagewanted=all&src=pmHigh School Heroes, After the Last Time Up]," ''New York Times'' <small>(retrieved 5 March 2013)</small>:
#*: But Manny Ramirez is '''living the dream'''; two weeks ago, he signed a quarter-million-dollar contract with the Cleveland Indians.
#* '''2004''' April 12, Andrew D. Arnold, "[http://www.time.com/time/arts/article/0,8599,609686,00.html Keeping It 'Riel']," ''Time'':
#*: Chester Brown '''lives the dream'''. . . . [W]ith the publication of his graphic novel, "Louis Riel," he not only has a hit, but also the accolades of the industry.
#* '''2006''' July 2, Nick Allen, [http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/news-and-comment/beckham-stands-down-as-captain-406387.html Beckham stands down as captain], ''The Independent'' (UK) <small>(retrieved 5 March 2013)</small>:
#*: Beckham choked back tears. . . . He said he had "'''lived the dream'''" but with a new manager taking over it was time for a new captain.

====Usage notes====
* Often used in the [[present participle|present participial]] form: {{m|en|living the dream}}.